GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 1
SENATE BILL 546
Short Title: Clean Energy Workforce & Innovation Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Senators Theodros and Salvador (Primary Sponsors).
Referred to: Rules and Operations of the Senate
March 26, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ENACT THE CLEAN ENERGY WORKFORCE AND INNOVATION ACT.
3 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
4 SECTION 1.(a) Article 10 of Chapter 143B of the General Statutes is amended by
5 adding a new Part to read:
6 "Part 8A. Clean Energy.
7 "§ 143B-451.2. Clean energy workforce and innovation.
8 (a) Title, purpose. – This Part shall be known and may be cited as "The Clean Energy
9 Workforce and Innovation Act". The purpose of this Act is to accomplish the following:
10 (1) Develop a skilled workforce in this State to support the deployment of
11 advanced nuclear energy, small modular reactors, and related clean energy
12 technologies and facilities.
13 (2) Accelerate clean energy innovation by streamlining regulatory processes for
14 small modular reactors and associated infrastructure, ensuring North Carolina
15 remains a leader in reliable, low-carbon energy.
16 (3) Expand economic opportunities in energy transition by investing in workforce
17 training, apprenticeships, and educational partnerships that equip North
18 Carolinians for high-paying, sustainable careers.
19 (4) Ensure equitable access to clean energy jobs by prioritizing workforce
20 development programs in communities affected by fossil fuel plant closures,
21 economically distressed areas, and underrepresented groups in the energy
22 sector.
23 (b) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this Part.
24 (1) Department. – The Department of Commerce.
25 (2) Energy sector skilled trade. – Operator certification, welding, precision
26 machining, grid integration and energy storage expertise, nuclear fuel
27 management, electrical work, instrumentation and control systems
28 capabilities, cyber security, reactor maintenance, or any other trade or
29 occupation related to nuclear energy facilities or generation that does not
30 require a four-year college degree.
31 (3) Institution of higher education. – Any public university, community college,
32 or technical training school in North Carolina offering programs in nuclear
33 technology, engineering, or energy-sector skilled trades.
34 (4) Small Modular Reactor (SMR). – A nuclear reactor with a capacity of less
35 than 500 megawatts per unit, designed for modular construction and advanced
36 safety features, including passive safety systems using natural cooling
*S546-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 mechanisms to prevent overheating; underground or sealed containment
2 systems; automatic fail-safe shutdown mechanisms; smaller core and lower
3 power density componentry; fuel choices that are accident tolerant or capable
4 of withstanding higher temperatures with lower risk; and security measures
5 reducing risks from sabotage, aircraft impact, or other external threats.
6 (c) Clean Energy Workforce Development Program. – There is established in the
7 Department of Commerce the Clean Energy Workforce Development Program (Program). The
8 Program shall be comprised of the following elements:
9 (1) Workforce development. – In conjunction with The University of North
10 Carolina and the Community Colleges System Office, the Department shall
11 develop a grant program for institutions of higher education in this State to
12 expedite and facilitate the expansion of nuclear technology and clean energy
13 training programs. The Department shall (i) develop guidelines for an
14 application process for institutions of higher education for the allocation of
15 funds granted pursuant to this section and (ii) prioritize awarding funds based
16 on the degree to which the institution has shown in the application the
17 following:
18 a. A viable plan to partner and create learning synergies with industry
19 leaders and employers to align training and real-world clean energy
20 needs.
21 b. The funding will be used for nuclear energy workforce needs,
22 including energy sector skilled trades.
23 (2) Apprenticeship development. – In conjunction with The University of North
24 Carolina and the Community Colleges System Office, the Department shall
25 develop a grant program for subsidizing the costs of qualifying employers for
26 paid apprenticeship positions for students in institutions of higher education
27 in the State in order to promote direct-to-hire pathways for participating
28 students to be prepared for and immediately fill nuclear energy industry
29 workforce needs. A qualifying employer is an employer currently operating
30 nuclear energy facilities in the State or in another state and construction
31 companies and other entities identified by such employers as having the
32 technical capabilities necessary to design, construct, and maintain nuclear
33 reactors and equipment for nuclear energy generation. The Department shall
34 (i) develop guidelines for an application process for qualifying employers for
35 the allocation of funds granted pursuant to this section and (ii) prioritize
36 awarding funds based on the degree to which the employer has shown, in the
37 application or otherwise, the following:
38 a. A viable plan to partner and create learning synergies and pre- and
39 post-graduation employment opportunities for student attending
40 institutions of higher education in the State.
41 b. The funding will be used to subsidize the total cost of the paid
42 apprenticeship program created by the qualifying employer and
43 stipends to participating apprentices to offset living costs.
44 c. The funding will be used to benefit economically disadvantaged
45 students. For purposes of this sub-subdivision, an economically
46 disadvantaged student is one that meets any one or more of the
47 following:
48 1. Qualifies for and receives a federal Pell Grant.
49 2. Is a dependent in a household with income below (i) eighty
50 percent (80%) of the state median income or (i) the federal
51 poverty line.
