1 (3) Compiling any available data on whether expanding North Carolina
2 businesses receive fewer benefits than out-of-State businesses that locate to
3 North Carolina.
4 (c) Impact Study. – The Department of Commerce shall study the effectiveness of the tax
5 incentives provided in this Article. This study shall include:
6 (1) Studying the distribution of tax incentives across new and expanding
7 businesses and industries.
8 (2) Examining data on economic recruitment for the period from 2005 through
9 the most recent year for which data are available by county, by industry type,
10 by size of investment, and by number of jobs, and other relevant information
11 to determine the pattern of business locations and expansions before and after
12 the enactment of this Article.
13 (3) Measuring the direct costs and benefits of the tax incentives.
14 (4) Compiling available information on the current use of incentives by other
15 states and whether that use is increasing or declining.
16 (d) Report. – The Department of Commerce shall report the results of these studies and
17 its recommendations to the General Assembly biennially with the first report due by June 1,
18 2009.2026.
19 "§ 105-129.83. Eligibility; forfeiture.
20 (a) Eligible Business. – A taxpayer is eligible for a credit under this Article only with
21 respect to activities occurring at an establishmenta location whose primary activity is listed in
22 this subsection. clean energy manufacturing. The primary activity of an establishmenta location
23 is determined based on the establishment's location's principal product or group of products
24 produced or distributed, or services rendered.
25 (1) Air courier services hub.
26 (2) Aircraft maintenance and repair.
27 (3) Company headquarters, but only if the additional eligibility requirements of
28 subsection (b) of this section are satisfied.
29 (4) Customer service call centers.
30 (5) Electronic shopping and mail order houses.
31 (6) Information technology and services.
32 (7) Manufacturing.
33 (8) Motorsports facility.
34 (9) Motorsports racing team.
35 (10) Research and development.
36 (11) Warehousing.
37 (12) Wholesale trade.
38 (b) Company Headquarters Eligibility. – A taxpayer is eligible for a credit under this
39 Article with respect to a company headquarters only if the taxpayer creates at least 75 new jobs
40 at the company headquarters within a 24-month period. A taxpayer that meets this job creation
41 requirement is eligible for credits under this Article with respect to the company headquarters for
42 three taxable years beginning with the year in which the job creation requirement is satisfied. A
43 taxpayer that creates an additional 75 new jobs at the company headquarters in a 24-month period
44 during a three-year eligibility period does not qualify for any extended eligibility period.
45 However, a taxpayer that creates an additional 75 new jobs at the company headquarters in a
46 24-month period after the completion of a three-year eligibility period is eligible for credits with
47 respect to the company headquarters for an additional three taxable years beginning in the year
48 in which the additional job creation requirement is satisfied.
49 (c) Wage Standard. – A taxpayer is eligible for a credit under this Article in a
50 development tier two or three area only if the taxpayer satisfies a wage standard. The taxpayer is
51 not required to satisfy a wage standard if the activity occurs in a development tier one area. Jobs
Senate Bill 546-First Edition Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 that are located within an urban progress zone, a port enhancement zone, or an agrarian growth
2 zone but not in a development tier one area satisfy the wage standard if they pay an average
3 weekly wage that is at least equal to ninety percent (90%) of the lesser of the average wage for
4 all insured private employers in the State and the average wage for all insured private employers
5 in the county. All other jobs satisfy the wage standard if they pay an average weekly wage that
6 is at least equal to the lesser of one hundred ten percent (110%) of the average wage for all
7 insured private employers in the State and ninety percent (90%) of the average wage for all
8 insured private employers in the county. The Department of Commerce shall annually publish
9 the wage standard for each county.
10 In making the wage calculation, the taxpayer shall include any jobs that were filled for at
11 least 1,600 hours during the calendar year the taxpayer engages in the activity that qualifies for
12 the credit even if those jobs are not filled at the time the taxpayer claims the credit. For a taxpayer
13 with a taxable year other than a calendar year, the taxpayer shall use the wage standard for the
14 calendar year in which the taxable year begins. Only full-time jobs are included when making
15 the wage calculation.
16 (d) Health Insurance. – A taxpayer is eligible for a credit under this Article only if the
17 taxpayer provides health insurance for all of the full-time jobs at the establishment location with
18 respect to which the credit is claimed when the taxpayer engages in the activity that qualifies for
19 the credit. For the purposes of this subsection, a taxpayer provides health insurance if it pays at
20 least fifty percent (50%) of the premiums for health care coverage that equals or exceeds the
21 minimum provisions of the basic health care plan of coverage recommended by the Small
22 Employer Carrier Committee pursuant to G.S. 58-50-125.requirements for small group health
23 benefit plans under State or federal law.
24 Each year that a taxpayer claims a credit or carryforward of a credit allowed under this
25 Article, the taxpayer shall provide with the tax return the taxpayer's certification that the taxpayer
26 continues to provide health insurance for all the jobs at the establishment location with respect
27 to which the credit was claimed. If the taxpayer ceases to provide health insurance for the jobs
28 during a taxable year, the credit expires, and the taxpayer may not take any remaining installment
29 or carryforward of the credit.expires.
30 (e) Environmental Impact. – A taxpayer is eligible for a credit allowed under this Article
31 only if the taxpayer certifies that, at the time the taxpayer claims the credit, there has not been a
32 final determination unfavorable to the taxpayer with respect to an environmental disqualifying
33 event. For the purposes of this section, a "final determination unfavorable to the taxpayer" occurs
34 when there is no further opportunity for the taxpayer to seek administrative or judicial appeal,
35 review, certiorari, or rehearing of the environmental disqualifying event and the disqualifying
36 event has not been reversed or withdrawn. No later than January 31 of each year, the Secretary
37 of Environmental Quality shall provide an annual report to the Department listing all
38 environmental disqualifying events for which a final determination unfavorable to the taxpayer
39 was made in the prior calendar year and shall provide the name of the taxpayer involved and the
40 date that the disqualifying event occurred.
41 (f) Safety and Health Programs. – A taxpayer is eligible for a credit allowed under this
42 Article only if the taxpayer certifies that, as of the time the taxpayer claims the credit, at the
43 establishment location with respect to which the credit is claimed, the taxpayer has no citations
44 under the Occupational Safety and Health Act that have become a final order within the past
45 three years for willful serious violations or for failing to abate serious violations. For the purposes
46 of this subsection, "serious violation" has the same meaning as in G.S. 95-127. The
47 Commissioner of Labor shall notify the Department of Revenue annually of all employers who
48 have had these citations become final orders within the past three years.
49 (g) Overdue Tax Debts. – A taxpayer is not eligible for a credit allowed under this Article
50 if, at the time the taxpayer claims the credit or an installment or carryforward of the credit, the
