1 taxpayer has received a notice of an overdue tax debt and that overdue tax debt has not been
2 satisfied or otherwise resolved.
3 (h) Expiration. – If, during the period that installments of a credit under this Article
4 accrue, the taxpayer is no longer engaged in one of the types of the business described in
5 subsection (a) of this section at the establishment location for which the credit was claimed, the
6 credit expires. If, during the period that installments of a credit under this Article accrue, the
7 number of jobs of an eligible company headquarters falls below the minimum number required
8 under subsection (b) of this section, any credit associated with that company headquarters
9 expires. When a credit expires, the taxpayer may not take any remaining installments of the
10 credit. The taxpayer may, however, take the portion of an installment that accrued in a previous
11 year and was carried forward to the extent permitted under G.S. 105-129.84. A change in the
12 development tier designation of the location of an establishmenta location does not result in
13 expiration of a credit under this Article.
14 (i) Forfeiture. – A taxpayer forfeits a credit allowed under this Article if the taxpayer was
15 not eligible for the credit for the calendar year in which the taxpayer engaged in the activity for
16 which the credit was claimed. A taxpayer forfeits a credit previously allowed under this Article
17 if a final determination unfavorable to the taxpayer with respect to an environmental
18 disqualifying event is made that is applicable to the year in which the activity occurred for which
19 the credit was claimed. In addition, a taxpayer forfeits a credit for investment in real property
20 under G.S. 105-129.89 if the taxpayer fails to timely create the number of required new jobs or
21 to timely make the required level of investment.investment under G.S. 105-129.89(b). A taxpayer
22 that forfeits a credit under this Article is liable for all past taxes avoided as a result of the credit
23 plus interest at the rate established under G.S. 105-241.21, computed from the date the taxes
24 would have been due if the credit had not been allowed. The past taxes and interest are due 30
25 days after the date the credit is forfeited; a taxpayer that fails to pay the past taxes and interest by
26 the due date is subject to the penalties provided in G.S. 105-236.
27 (j) Change in Ownership of Business. – As used in this subsection, the term "business"
28 means a taxpayer or an establishment.a location. The sale, merger, consolidation, conversion,
29 acquisition, or bankruptcy of a business, or any transaction by which an existing business
30 reformulates itself as another business, does not create new eligibility in a succeeding business
31 with respect to credits for which the predecessor was not eligible under this Article. A successor
32 business may, however, take any credit or carried-over portion of a credit that its predecessor
33 could have taken if it had a tax liability. The acquisition of a business is a new investment that
34 creates new eligibility in the acquiring taxpayer under this Article if any of the following
35 conditions are met:
36 (1) The business closed before it was acquired.
37 (2) The business was required to file a notice of plant closing or mass layoff under
38 the federal Worker Adjustment and Retraining Notification Act, 29 U.S.C. §
39 2101, before it was acquired.
40 (3) The business was acquired by its employees directly or indirectly through an
41 acquisition company under an employee stock option transaction or another
42 similar mechanism. For the purpose of this subdivision, "acquired" means that
43 as part of the initial purchase of a business by the employees, the purchase
44 included an agreement for the employees through the employee stock option
45 transaction or another similar mechanism to obtain one of the following:
46 a. Ownership of more than fifty percent (50%) of the business.
47 b. Ownership of not less than forty percent (40%) of the business within
48 seven years if the business has tangible assets with a net book value in
49 excess of one hundred million dollars ($100,000,000) and has the
50 majority of its operations located in a development tier one area.
