20 "§ 105-129.84. (See notes) Tax election;liability eligibility; cap; carryforwards; limitations.
21 (a) Tax Election. –Liability Limitation. – The credits provided in this Article are allowed
22 against the franchise tax levied in Article 3 of this Chapter, the income taxes levied in Article 4
23 of this Chapter, and the gross premiums tax levied in Article 8B of this Chapter. The taxpayer
24 may divide a credit between the taxes against which it is allowed. Carryforwards of a credit may
25 be divided between the taxes against which it is allowed without regard to the original election
26 regarding the division of the credit.
27 (b) Cap. – The credits allowed under this Article may not exceed fifty percent (50%) of
28 the cumulative amount of taxes against which they may be claimed for the taxable year, reduced
29 by the sum of all other credits allowed against those taxes, except tax payments made by or on
30 behalf of the taxpayer. This limitation applies to the cumulative amount of credit, including
31 carryforwards, claimed by the taxpayer under this Article for the taxable year.
32 (c) Carryforward. – Unless a longer carryforward period applies, any unused portion of
33 a credit allowed under G.S. 105-129.87 or G.S. 105-129.88 may be carried forward for the
34 succeeding five years, and any unused portion of a credit allowed under G.S. 105-129.89 may be
35 carried forward for the succeeding 15 years. If the Secretary of Commerce makes a written
36 determination that the taxpayer is expected to purchase or lease, and place in service in
37 connection with an eligible business within a two-year period, at least one hundred fifty million
38 dollars ($150,000,000) worth of business and real property, any unused portion of a credit under
39 this Article with respect to the establishment that satisfies that condition may be carried forward
40 for the succeeding 20 years. If the taxpayer does not make the required level of investment, the
41 taxpayer shall apply the standard carryforward period rather than the 20-year carryforward
42 period.
43 (d) Statute of Limitations. – Notwithstanding Article 9 of this Chapter, a taxpayer shall
44 claim a credit under this Article within six months after the date set by statute for the filing of the
45 return, including any extensions of that date.
46 (e) Credit Treated as Tax Payment. – The owner of a pass-through entity that claims a
47 credit under this Article may treat some or all of the credit claimed as a tax payment made by or
48 on behalf of the taxpayer. A credit claimed that is treated as a tax payment is subject to all
49 provisions of this section. A credit claimed that is treated as a tax payment does not accrue interest
50 under G.S. 105-241.21 if the payment is determined to be an overpayment. A taxpayer that elects
Page 10 Senate Bill 546-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 to have a credit claimed under this Article treated as a tax payment must make this election when
2 the return is filed.
3 "§ 105-129.85. (See notes) Fees and reports.
4 (a) Fee. – When filing a return for a taxable year in which the taxpayer engaged in activity
5 for which the taxpayer is eligible for a credit under this Article, the taxpayer shall pay the
6 Department of Revenue a fee of five hundred dollars ($500.00) for each type ofthe credit the
7 taxpayer claims or intends to claim with respect to an establishment.a location. The fee is due at
8 the time the return is due for the taxable year in which the taxpayer engaged in the activity for
9 which the taxpayer is eligible for a credit. No credit is allowed under this Article for a taxable
10 year until all outstanding fees have been paid. Fees collected under this section shall be credited
11 to the General Fund.
12 (b) Report. – The Department must include in the economic incentives report required by
13 G.S. 105-256 the following information itemized by credit and by taxpayer:
14 (1) The number and amount of credits generated and taken for each credit allowed
15 in this Article.
16 (2) The number and development tier area of new jobs with respect to which
17 credits were generated and to which credits were taken.
18 (3) The cost and development tier area of business property with respect to which
19 credits were generated and to which credits were taken.
20 (4) The cost and development tier area of real property investment with respect
21 to which credits were generated and to which credits were taken.
22 "§ 105-129.86. (See notes) Substantiation.
23 (a) Records. – To claim a credit allowed by this Article, the taxpayer shall provide any
24 information required by the Secretary of Revenue. Every taxpayer claiming a credit under this
25 Article shall maintain and make available for inspection by the Secretary of Revenue any records
26 the Secretary considers necessary to determine and verify the amount of the credit to which the
27 taxpayer is entitled. The burden of proving eligibility for the credit and the amount of the credit
28 shall rest upon the taxpayer, and no credit shall be allowed to a taxpayer that fails to maintain
29 adequate records or to make them available for inspection.
30 (b) Documentation. – Each taxpayer shall provide with the tax return qualifying
31 information for each credit claimed under this Article. The qualifying information shall be in the
32 form prescribed by the Secretary and shall be signed and affirmed by the individual who signs
33 the taxpayer's tax return. The information required by this subsection is information
34 demonstrating that the taxpayer has met the conditions for qualifying for a credit and any
35 carryforwards and includes the following:
36 (1) The physical location of the jobs and investment with respect to which the
37 credit is claimed, including the street address and the development tier
38 designation of the establishment.location.
39 (2) The type of business with respect to which the credit is claimed and the
40 average weekly wage at the establishment location with respect to which the
41 credit is claimed.
42 (3) Any other qualifying information related to a specific credit allowed under
43 this Article.
44 "§ 105-129.87. (See notes) Credit for creating jobs.
45 (a) Credit. – A taxpayer that meets the eligibility requirements set out in G.S. 105-129.83
46 and satisfies the threshold requirement for new job creation in this State under subsection (b) of
47 this section during the taxable year is allowed a credit for creating jobs. The amount of the credit
48 for each new job created is set out in the table below and is based on the development tier
49 designation of the county in which the job is located. If the job is located in an urban progress
50 zone, a port enhancement zone, or an agrarian growth zone, the amount of the credit is increased
51 by one thousand dollars ($1,000) per job. In addition, if a job located in an urban progress zone,
Senate Bill 546-First Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a port enhancement zone, or an agrarian growth zone is filled by a resident of that zone or by a
2 long-term unemployed worker, the amount of the credit is increased by an additional two
3 thousand dollars ($2,000) per job.
4 Area Development Tier Amount of Credit
5 Tier One $12,500
6 Tier Two 5,000
7 Tier Three 750
8 (b) Threshold. – The applicable threshold is the appropriate amount set out in the
9 following table based on the development tier designation of the county where the new jobs are
10 created during the taxable year. If the taxpayer creates new jobs at more than one eligible
11 establishment in a county during the taxable year, the threshold applies to the aggregate number
12 of new jobs created at all eligible establishments within the county during that year. If the
13 taxpayer creates new jobs at eligible establishments in different counties during the taxable year,
14 the threshold applies separately to the aggregate number of new jobs created at eligible
15 establishments in each county. If the taxpayer creates new jobs in an urban progress zone, a port
16 enhancement zone, or an agrarian growth zone, the applicable threshold is the one for a
17 development tier one area. New jobs created in an urban progress zone, a port enhancement zone,
18 or an agrarian growth zone are not aggregated with jobs created at any other eligible
19 establishments regardless of county.
20 Area Development Tier Threshold
21 Tier One 5
22 Tier Two 10
23 Tier Three 15
24 (c) Calculation. – A job is located in a county, an urban progress zone, a port
25 enhancement zone, or an agrarian growth zone if more than fifty percent (50%) of the employee's
26 duties are performed in the county or the zone. The number of new jobs a taxpayer creates during
27 the taxable year is determined by subtracting the average number of full-time employees the
28 taxpayer had in this State during the 12-month period preceding the beginning of the taxable year
29 from the average number of full-time employees the taxpayer has in this State during the taxable
30 year.
31 (d) Installments. – The credit may not be taken in the taxable year in which the new jobs
32 are created. Instead, the credit shall be taken in equal installments over the four years following
33 the taxable year in which the new jobs were created and is conditional upon the continued
34 maintenance of those jobs by the taxpayer. If, in one of the four years in which the installment of
35 a credit accrues, a job is no longer filled, the credit with respect to that job expires, and the
36 taxpayer may not take any remaining installment of the credit with respect to that job. If, in one
37 of the years in which the installment of a credit accrues, the number of the taxpayer's full-time
38 employees falls below the sum of the applicable threshold and the number of full-time employees
39 the taxpayer had in the year before the year in which the taxpayer qualified for the credit, the
40 credits with respect to all of the new jobs expire, and the taxpayer may not take any remaining
41 installments of the credits. When a credit expires under this subsection, the taxpayer may,
42 however, take the portion of an installment that accrued in a previous year and was carried
43 forward to the extent permitted under G.S. 105-129.84.
44 (e) Transferred Jobs. – Jobs transferred from one area in the State to another area in the
45 State are not considered new jobs for purposes of this section. Jobs that were located in this State
46 and that are transferred to the taxpayer from a related member of the taxpayer are not considered
47 new jobs for purposes of this section. If, in one of the four years in which the installment of a
48 credit accrues, the job with respect to which the credit was claimed is moved to an area in a
49 higher-numbered development tier or out of an urban progress zone, a port enhancement zone,
50 or an agrarian growth zone, the remaining installments of the credit are allowed only to the extent
51 they would have been allowed if the job was initially created in the area to which it was moved.
