General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 Tier Three 2,000,000
2 (d) Expiration. – As used in this subsection, the term "disposed of" means disposed of,
3 taken out of service, or moved out of State. If, in one of the four years in which the installment
4 of a credit accrues, the business property with respect to which the credit was claimed is disposed
5 of, the credit expires, and the taxpayer may not take any remaining installment of the credit for
6 that business property unless the cost of that business property is offset in the same taxable year
7 by the taxpayer's new investment in eligible business property placed in service in the same
8 county, as provided in this subsection. If, during the taxable year, the taxpayer disposed of the
9 business property for which installments remain, there has been a net reduction in the cost of all
10 the taxpayer's eligible business property that are in service in the same county as the business
11 property that was disposed of, and the amount of this reduction is greater than twenty percent
12 (20%) of the cost of the business property that was disposed of, then the credit for the business
13 property that was disposed of expires. If the amount of the net reduction is equal to twenty percent
14 (20%) or less of the cost of the business property that was disposed of, or if there is no net
15 reduction, then the credit does not expire. In determining the amount of any net reduction during
16 the taxable year, the cost of business property the taxpayer placed in service during the taxable
17 year and for which the taxpayer claims a credit under Article 3A or Article 3B of this Chapter
18 may not be included in the cost of all the taxpayer's eligible business property that is in service.
19 If in a single taxable year business property with respect to two or more credits in the same county
20 are disposed of, the net reduction in the cost of all the taxpayer's eligible business property that
21 is in service in the same county is compared to the total cost of all the business property for which
22 credits expired in order to determine whether the remaining installments of the credits are
23 forfeited.
24 The expiration of a credit does not prevent the taxpayer from taking the portion of an
25 installment that accrued in a previous year and was carried forward to the extent permitted under
26 G.S. 105-129.84.
27 (e) Transferred Property. – If, in one of the four years in which the installment of a credit
28 accrues, the business property with respect to which the credit was claimed is moved to a county
29 in a higher-numbered development tier or out of an urban progress zone, a port enhancement
30 zone, or an agrarian growth zone, the remaining installments of the credit are allowed only to the
31 extent they would have been allowed if the business property had been placed in service initially
32 in the area to which it was moved. If, in one of the four years in which the installment of a credit
33 accrues, the business property with respect to which a credit was claimed is moved to a county
34 in a lower-numbered development tier or an urban progress zone, a port enhancement zone, or
35 an agrarian growth zone, the remaining installments of the credit shall be calculated as if the
36 business property had been placed in service initially in the area to which it was moved.
37 (f) Wage Standard. – For the purposes of this section, a taxpayer satisfies the wage
38 standard requirement of G.S. 105-129.83 only if the taxpayer satisfies the requirement with
39 respect to all of the jobs at the establishment, considered collectively, with respect to which a
40 credit is claimed.
41 (g) No Double Credit. – A taxpayer may not claim a credit under this section with respect
42 to business property for which the taxpayer claims a credit under G.S. 105-129.9 or
43 G.S. 105-129.9A.
44 "§ 105-129.89. (See notes) Credit for investment in real property.
45 (a) Credit. – If a taxpayer that has purchased or leased real property in a development tier
46 one area begins to use the property in an eligible business during the taxable year, the taxpayer
47 is allowed a credit equal to thirty percent (30%) of the eligible investment amount if all of the
48 eligibility requirements of G.S. 105-129.83 and of subsection (b) of this section are met. For the
49 purposes of this section, property is located in a development tier one area if the area the property
50 is located in was a development tier one area at the time the taxpayer made a written application
51 for the determination required under subsection (b) of this section. The eligible investment
Page 14 Senate Bill 546-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 amount is the lesser of (i) the cost of the property and (ii) the amount by which the cost of all of
2 the real property the taxpayer is using in this State in an eligible business on the last day of the
3 taxable year exceeds the cost of all of the real property the taxpayer was using in this State in an
4 eligible business on the last day of the base year. The base year is that year, of the three
5 immediately preceding taxable years, in which the taxpayer was using the most real property in
6 this State in an eligible business. In the case of property that is leased, the cost of the property is
7 not determined as provided in G.S. 105-129.81 but is considered to be the taxpayer's lease
8 payments over a seven-year period, plus any expenditures made by the taxpayer to improve the
9 property before it is used by the taxpayer if the expenditures are not reimbursed or credited by
10 the lessor. The entire credit may not be taken for the taxable year in which the property is first
11 used in an eligible business but shall be taken in equal installments over the seven years following
12 the taxable year in which the property is first used in an eligible business. When part of the
13 property is first used in an eligible business in one year and part is first used in an eligible business
14 in a later year, separate credits may be claimed for the amount of property first used in an eligible
15 business in each year. The basis in any real property for which a credit is allowed under this
16 section shall be reduced by the amount of credit allowable.
17 (b) Determination by the Secretary of Commerce. – A taxpayer is eligible for the credit
18 allowed under this section with respect to an establishment only if the Secretary of Commerce
19 makes a written determination that the taxpayer is expected to purchase or lease and use in an
20 eligible business at that establishment within a three-year period at least ten million dollars
21 ($10,000,000) of real property and that the establishment that is the subject of the credit will
22 create at least 200 new jobs within two years of the time that the property is first used in an
23 eligible business. If the taxpayer fails to timely make the required level of investment or fails to
24 timely create the required number of new jobs, the taxpayer forfeits the credit as provided in G.S.
25 105-129.83.
26 (c) Mixed Use Property. – If the taxpayer uses only part of the property in an eligible
27 business, the amount of the credit allowed under this section is reduced by multiplying it by a
28 fraction, the numerator of which is the square footage of the property used in an eligible business
29 and the denominator of which is the total square footage of the property.
30 (d) Expiration. – If, in one of the seven years in which the installment of a credit accrues,
31 the property with respect to which the credit was claimed is no longer used in an eligible business,
32 the credit expires, and the taxpayer may not take any remaining installment of the credit. If, in
33 one of the seven years in which the installment of a credit accrues, part of the property with
34 respect to which the credit was claimed is no longer used in an eligible business, the remaining
35 installments of the credit shall be reduced by multiplying it by the fraction described in subsection
36 (c) of this section. If, in one of the years in which the installment of a credit accrues and by which
37 the taxpayer is required to have created 200 new jobs at the property, the total number of
38 employees the taxpayer employs at the property with respect to which the credit is claimed is less
39 than 200, the credit expires, and the taxpayer may not take any remaining installment of the
40 credit.
41 In each of these cases, the taxpayer may nonetheless take the portion of an installment that
42 accrued in a previous year and was carried forward to the extent permitted under G.S.
43 105-129.84.
44 (e) No Double Credit. – A taxpayer may not claim a credit under this section with respect
45 to real property for which a credit is claimed under G.S. 105-129.12 or G.S. 105-129.12A.
